<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cairo Talks Focus on Security, Civilian Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cairo Talks Focus on Security, Civilian Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Deep' Differences Explored </H4>

<F P=102> NC1904111594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1015 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1904111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 19 Apr (MENA)--The Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations resumed today with the objective of implementing 
the Gaza-Jericho agreement. The Palestinian side to the talks 
is chaired by Dr. Nabil Sha'th, Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat's political adviser, and the Israeli side by General 
Amnon Shahaq, Israeli deputy chief of staff. 
  Dr. Sha'th affirmed that the negotiators will discuss during 
their meeting today the same subjects they started discussing 
yesterday and on which they made no progress. 
  Palestinian sources have affirmed to MENA that the two sides 
are trying to overcome the big obstacles before the 
negotiations, especially in the framework of the two committees, 
the Security Committee and the Legal Affairs Committee. 
Foremost of these issues is legal jurisdiction over the Gaza 
Strip and the Jericho area, as well as control over the 
crossings and the border points and the release of the 
Palestinian detainees who are estimated to be around 10,400 
people, according to the statistics of the International Red 
Cross. 
  Palestinian sources clarified that the Palestinian 
negotiators insist that all Palestinian detainees should be 
released, irrespective of their political affiliation. The 
objective is to guarantee that no split takes place inside the 
Palestinian ranks. On the other hand, the Israeli side insists 
on not releasing any of the Hamas members since some of its 
members recently carried out some suicide attacks on Israelis. 
  The sources said that the Palestinian-Israeli Civilian 
Affairs Committee will today discuss the subject of contacts in 
the Gaza Strip and the Jericho area, in addition to providing 
the Palestinian side with a number of wavelengths and 
frequencies to be used by the police and other services. 
  The sources pointed out that in the case where the deep 
differences between the two sides continue over many basic 
issues, the leaderships of the two sides will have to intervene 
to rescue the negotiations from collapse. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

