<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomatic Changes Linked to Polish Arms Deal `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomatic Changes Linked to Polish Arms Deal `Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1804141294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 18 Apr 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1804141294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abdallah Hammudah: "Yemeni Foreign Minister </F>
Returns Socialist Party Diplomats to Sanaa"] 
  [Excerpt] London, Sanaa, Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Yemeni 
Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim Basindwah has reshuffled staff 
in Yemeni embassies abroad. The reshuffle affects in particular 
diplomats who come from southern Yemen and those who have close 
links with the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP], one of the two 
parties to the Yemeni political crisis. The other party to the 
crisis is the General People's Congress [GPC]. 
  The most notable feature of this reshuffle is the return of 
diplomats "who do not enjoy Sanaa's trust" to Yemen. 
  A source close to the YSP rejected this reshuffle, pointing 
out that a number of embassies have not received their expenses 
for many months, in order to force YSP diplomats to return. The 
source warned that, if these embassies do not receive their 
allowances, Aden will allocate to them allowances that guarantee 
the continuation of their work, lest Yemeni diplomacy become a 
partisan tool in the hands of the GPC. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that Yemeni embassies run by a 
southerner occupying the ambassador post usually has at least 
one northerner on whom Sanaa relies in running most affairs and 
contacts, while the head of the diplomatic mission remains just 
a symbol. 
  A well-informed source has said that the recent diplomatic 
reshuffle is a reaction to the crisis caused by Muhammad Sharaf, 
Yemeni charge d'affaires in Warsaw, who provoked a big clamor 
when he revealed a secret arms deal which the Economic Military 
Establishment had concluded with Poland for the northern 
military command. He refused to issue entry visas for Polish 
arms companies' officials to enable them to visit Sanaa and 
complete the negotiations concerning the deal. 
  It is worth mentioning that the Yemeni Foreign Ministry 
granted some Polish officials visas upon their arrival at Sanaa 
airport. Upon his arrival in Warsaw last Sunday, Fu'ad Sawwaf 
Sivjik [as transliterated], sales director of the Polish company 
Cenzin, said that he had signed a contract worth tens of 
millions of dollars to supply the Yemeni Defense Ministry with 
arms, ammunition, and equipment. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

