<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Comments on Kurdish State, Water Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy Comments on Kurdish State, Water Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1604110794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0800 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1604110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, 16 Apr (MENA)--'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Rifa'i, 
Syrian ambassador to Turkey, has stressed that his country is 
against the establishment of an independent Kurdish state in 
northern Iraq, and that Syria will engage in methods other than 
diplomacy to prevent this from happening. 
  In an interview with a MENA correspondent in Ankara, 
al-Rifa'i pointed out that Iraq must be united as any other Arab 
country. He noted that although the Syrian and Iraqi 
governments have differences, the establishment of a separate 
state in northern Iraq is another matter. The differences, he 
added, will not prevent Syria from using its means to stand 
alongside the Iraqi people in the face of this conspiracy. He 
also stressed his country will not use the Kurdistan Workers 
Party, which is outlawed in Turkey, as a source of pressure on 
Ankara to reach a water sharing agreement. 
  Al-Rifa'i pointed out that Syria has as much right to the 
water in the Tigris and Euphrates as Turkey does, adding that 
the Syrian Government still wants an agreement among Syria, 
Iraq, and Turkey on the Tigris and Euphrates water, because the 
present situation cannot continue. He said his country is not 
against Turkey's selling water to Israel, but it prefers for 
Ankara to play the water card to put pressure on Israel to 
withdraw from the occupied Arab territories. 
  Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said during his 
recent 
visit to Turkey that Israel is a democratic state. Ambassador 
al-Rifa'i said that these remarks are meant to pacify the 
Turkish people and to convince them that Israel is a 
peace-loving country and that it is the Arabs who are rejecting 
peace. 
  The Syrian ambassador stressed that Peres lied, since more 
than 12,000 Palestinian prisoners are locked up in Israeli 
jails. He added that Israel has failed to implement the 
Gaza-Jericho agreement on time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

