<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Peres Reportedly Accept Full Golan Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin, Peres Reportedly Accept Full Golan Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1904182594 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1904182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen] </F>
  [Text] The prime minister's candor in today's session of 
the Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee was 
surprising, at least in view of the fact that merely two days 
ago, Rabin was furious at the disclosure of the very existence 
of the General Staff working papers on the Israeli-Syrian 
negotiations. 
  Senior political and military elements told us today: Rabin 
has just confirmed what everybody has known for some time: He 
and Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres have accepted the concept of 
a full IDF [Israel Defense Forces] withdrawal from the Golan 
Heights, including the evacuation of all the settlements. The 
ideal line suggested in the IDF treatise on partial withdrawal 
lies 5 to 8 km away from the mountain ridge line -- the line 
from which the Lake of Tiberias and the Hula Valley can be 
observed. Today Rabin said: I am ready to move west of there 
-- namely, up to the ridge line itself in the first stage and 
probably completely off the Golan Heights in the second stage. 
  Hence, the haggling with the Syrians will be over other 
issues: security arrangements, the manning of the Golan Heights 
early warning stations, and the gradual nature of withdrawal. 
As for acreage, the die has been cast. 
  [Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network in Hebrew at 
1700 GMT on 19 April, in a report by political correspondent 
Gadi Sukenik, adds: "There is doubt in Jerusalem that progress 
with Syria is feasible" at this time, because "at this stage, 
Peres and Rabin are not enthusiastic about either a U.S. visit 
or any meaningful progress with Syria. At this stage, they 
would prefer to postpone it until the IDF completes its 
withdrawal, or rather, to turn to the Syrian track only after 
the first stage of the Israel-PLO agreement is implemented." 
Sukenik adds: "Almost every element involved in this issue 
believes that when the process gets down to brass tacks, there 
will be talk of full peace and full, or almost full, withdrawal 
from the Golan."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

