<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Ready To Go Beyond IDF Recommendation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin Ready To Go Beyond IDF Recommendation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1904145894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1400 GMT 19 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1904145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin today told the Knesset 
Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee that he is ready for a 
greater withdrawal on the Golan than that recommended by the 
IDF's [Israel Defense Forces] General Staff. The prime 
minister's statement was made in reply to a question from 
Knesset Member [MK] Beni Begin. 
  Our correspondent Hayim Hecht reports that the prime 
minister 
stressed that the working paper he received from Major General 
Ilan Biran did not refer to a total IDF withdrawal from the 
Golan. 
  Also at today's Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense 
Committee 
session, Yitzhaq Rabin, prime minister and defense minister, 
said the regular troops are in a difficult situation, because 
all the men are tied up in operational activity in Judaea, 
Samaria, and the Gaza Strip. Rabin noted that instead of the 
planned six months of training, the regular troops were barely 
receiving three months, and if the situation continues, the 
level of preparedness will be affected. The prime minister 
added that there are many friction-prone sites in Hebron, which 
are liable to lead to a conflagration. For that reason, the best 
units are tied up in that location. 
  [A related report by Tamar Asalem on Tel Aviv IDF Radio in 
Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 19 April adds: "The prime minister said 
that Jordan may not attend the Washington talks because of the 
naval blockade imposed by the United States on al-'Aqabah. He 
believes, however, that an agreement with Jordan will be 
possible only after one is achieved with Syria. 
  ["Discussing the Syrian issue, the prime minister stated 
that 
there is a principle of international presence on the Golan, but 
he did not specify the nature of the presence. The prime 
minister added that all decisions would be made by the political 
echelons, and all publicized documents merely represent the 
process of data gathering and preparatory work. 
  ["MK Beni Begin told the prime minister that he understood 
that the General Staff recommendations specified a smaller 
withdrawal area than Rabin found acceptable. Rabin's simple 
reply: Yes. There is no argument that in the military sense, 
the present line is better than any line lying farther to the 
west, but our work is based on a certain political reality."] 

</TEXT>

