<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister: No Trend Shown by New Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Prime Minister: No Trend Shown by New Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104091994 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 0730 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Kuwait, 21 Apr -- Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad, first 
deputy prime minister and minister of foreign affairs, has 
stressed that there are no political parties in Kuwait and that 
the establishment of parties would not be allowed there. 
  In an interview with AL-ANBA today, Shaykh Sabah said that 
the new government had not been chosen to represent any 
particular trend or orientation, but had been chosen from all 
the sons of Kuwait. 
  He added that what distinguishes Kuwait is that all its sons 
belong to one family and there is no discrimination or 
preference for any of its sons over any other except on the 
basis of his abilities and aptitudes. 
  Al-Sabah said that even if their opinions differ on some 
matters, the opinions of all Kuwaitis ultimately serve the 
interest of Kuwait. 
  He said that the new government faces the challenges of 
implementing the law and extending the rule of law, and will not 
be a government of challenges to persons or trends as some 
people are saying. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

