<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troops Deployed as Demonstrations Hit Medani </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Troops Deployed as Demonstrations Hit Medani </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004135094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 20 Apr 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM2004135094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Uthman Mirghani: "Demonstrations Against `High </F>
Prices'; Forces Deployed in Medani"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- Well-informed Sudanese sources have 
said that Medani, the second largest city in Sudan after 
Khartoum, has witnessed widespread demonstrations against high 
prices and living conditions, and that Central Security and Army 
troops have been deployed in the streets to guard the main 
sensitive sites in the city. 
  These domestic developments coincided with reports of the 
abduction of Sudanese Ambassador to Mogadishu 'Abd-al-Baqi 
Muhammad Hasan yesterday by gunmen while he was on his way to 
his office from his residence. 
  With regard to the demonstrations in Medani, south of 
Khartoum, the sources said that the demonstrations started the 
day before yesterday and continued yesterday. University and 
high school students and a number of workers and employees took 
part in the demonstrations. 
  There have been no reports of casualties. However, sources 
told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the demonstrations were noisy and 
violent. 
  Medani has over the past months witnessed widespread 
demonstrations against living conditions, during which 
demonstrators burned some installations, banks, and gas 
stations. The security forces' intervention led to clashes and 
casualties. 
  There have also been reports of demonstrations in al-Qadarif 
city in east Sudan. 
  Meanwhile, the Sudanese Government made contacts with the 
various Somali parties yesterday to secure the release of 
Ambassador 'Abd-al-Baqi Muhammad Hasan, 48, who was abducted by 
three gunmen. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

