<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Libyan Committee To Mediate Between Factions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Libyan Committee To Mediate Between Factions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004090094 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 19 Apr 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2004090094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ahmad Muwaffaq Zaydan: "Libyan Mediation Between </F>
Afghan Factions"] 
  [Text] Peshawar -- A nine-member Libyan committee headed by 
Dr. Mukhtar Ahmad Dayrah, dean of the Da'wah and Religious 
Principles College, has arrived in Peshawar to mediate between 
the warring Afghan factions. Dayrah told AL-HAYAH yesterday 
that the committee stemmed from a conference called for by the 
ulema and mosque preachers in Libya during the month of Ramadan. 
During that conference, four committees were formed to go to 
Islamic hotbeds of tension to help put an end to Muslim 
tragedies. "One committee proceeded to Somalia, a second 
committee went to Bosnia-Herzegovina, a third to the Kurds, and 
a fourth to Afghanistan." 
  On the reasons for the committee's late arrival, he said 
that 
"the U.S. blockade against Libya and visa procedures and 
complications contributed to the delay." 
  The committee chairman denied the existence of any 
preconceived plan. He said: "We are judges and we must hear 
the views of all parties and then give our opinion as to how the 
problem could be solved." He urged all the factions "not to 
waste the gains of 14 years of jihad." He added: "We have 
long-standing relations with the mujahidin. We do not object to 
mediation by any country for the desired peace. Libya is not a 
state neighboring Afghanistan. We have no interests there and we 
do not covet its wealth. All we want is to see peace 
established there." 
  Informed Afghan sources told AL-HAYAH yesterday that Afghan 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani and Prime Minister Golboddin 
Hekmatyar have accepted the Libyan mediation which coincides 
with the work of other Afghan and non-Afghan committees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13479 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes077_p_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104005694 Tripoli Voice of Greater Arab Homeland in 
Arabic 2315 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Voice of Greater Arab Homeland </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The delegation of imams, preachers, teachers of 
the holy Koran and teachers of Arabic and Islamic studies 
continued their meetings with the parties to the conflict in 
Afghanistan. Thus, the delegation met in Peshawar today Mohammad 
Imam, representative of Afghan President Borhanoddin Rabbani, 
Qotboddin Helal, deputy prime minister and representative of 
Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar, and a number of 
representatives of organizations and parties in Afghanistan. 
This falls within the framework of the efforts made by the 
Great Jamahiriyah to bring about reconciliation among the 
warring factions in Afghanistan and end their in-fighting. 
[passage omitted] 
  During the meeting Deputy Prime Minister Qotboddin Helal 
hailed the stands taken by the Great 1 September Revolution 
towards the causes of Islam and Muslims. He talked about the 
prominent role played by the brother leader of the revolution 
[Mu'ammar al- Qadhdhafi] in uniting the Afghan organizations 
during the period of resistance. He also expressed his thanks 
and appreciation for the Great Jamahiriyah's initiative aimed at 
achieving reconciliation among the parties to the conflict, 
restoring peace to Afghanistan and ending the in-fighting among 
brethren. 
  Mohammad Imam, representative of President Borhanoddin 
Rabbani, and Qotboddin Helal, representative of Prime Minister 
Golboddin Hekmatyar, expressed their readiness to offer all the 
facilities to ensure the success of the mission of the Libyan 
delegation. They also said that the Council of Coordination was 
prepared to declare a cease-fire during the mission of the 
Libyan delegation. The two men stressed their full desire to 
reach a fair solution which would satisfy all parties with a 
view to restoring security, stability and peace to Afghanistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

