<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Secret' Israeli-Syrian Talks Parallel Bilaterals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Secret' Israeli-Syrian Talks Parallel Bilaterals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2004090294 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 20 Apr 94 pp A1, A10 </F>
<F P=103> TA2004090294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Ambassador Itamar Rabinovich, head of the 
Israeli delegation to the talks with Syria, has been holding 
secret talks with Walid al-Mu'allim, Syria's ambassador in 
Washington, with the aim of furthering the peace negotiations 
between the two states. The meetings between the two ambassadors 
were held parallel to the official rounds of talks between the 
two states in Washington and in between rounds. 
  The meetings were attended by senior officials from the U.S. 
State Department dealing with the peace process. Some of the 
meetings were held at the home of Edward Djerejian when he was 
assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs. Dennis 
Ross, head of the American peace team, participated in some of 
the meetings. 
  When Rabinovich took up his post as ambassador in Washington 
in early 1993, Jerusalem hoped he would maintain a secret track 
with his counterpart, Ambassador Mu'allim, who was seen as more 
flexible and possessing more contacts with the Syrian top 
echelon than Muwaffaq al-'Allaf, head of the Syrian delegation 
to the bilateral peace talks. 
  Political sources in Jerusalem said yesterday that they 
believe that the Rabinovich-Mu'allim talks did not make much 
progress since neither received sufficient room to maneuver from 
their masters -- Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Syrian 
President Hafiz al-Asad. Nevertheless, the secret track is used 
to transmit messages between Jerusalem and Damascus and to 
assist in clarifying matters in the formal talks. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

