<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Department Slated To Move to Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Department Slated To Move to Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2104110594 Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' in Arabic 21 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN2104110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo--It has become certain that the PLO Political 
Department will be moved from Tunis to Cairo within the next 
weeks. 
  AKHBAR AL-USBU' learned that final preparations have been 
completed to move the Political Department. Informed sources 
expect that this will be the beginning of moving all PLO 
departments from Tunis to Cairo in the coming months. 
  Meanwhile, the Tunisian Government has decided not to renew 
the residency of any Palestinian in Tunisia as of late last 
month. The government gave instructions to the concerned 
authorities to deport any Palestinian as soon as his residency 
expires. Scores of Palestinians, whose residency permits 
expired, have been deported, and all Palestinians are expected 
to be deported from Tunisia by the end of this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13522 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes077dd_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hamas Claims Responsibility for Attack on Settlers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hamas Claims Responsibility for Attack on Settlers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2104092694 Paris AFP in English 0900 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2104092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gaza City, Occupied Gaza Strip, April 21 (AFP) -- 
The Islamic Resistance Movement Hamas claimed responsibility 
Thursday [21 April] for ambushing two Jewish settlers who were 
wounded on the Gaza Strip. 
  Hamas announced in a statement that Wednesday's shooting was 
the "first, swift response against continued Israeli arrests of 
its members." 
  Israel has arrested nearly 500 Islamic fundamentalist 
suspects, according to Palestinian sources, in a bid to break up 
the Hamas network. About 240 were detained on the Gaza Strip 
alone this week. 
  Meanwhile, clashes continued on the strip. Soldiers shot and 
wounded three Palestinians in Gaza City and two more in nearby 
Jabaliya refugee camp, Palestinian sources said. 
  Military officials said two settlers driving a car near the 
Gush Katif settlement were shot by Palestinian gunmen on 
Wednesday evening. 
  "Two of our fighters ambushed a car carrying two settlers 
... 
the bullets of 'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam were awaiting them and our 
fighters opened fire on them using M-16 guns." 'Izz-al-Din 
al-Qassam is the Hamas military wing. 
  The typed message warned that the operation, carried out by 
the "clandestine unit number 7," will be followed by others 
"with the dawn of every day, until the end of all occupation of 
our land." 
  HAMAS carried out two bus bombings this month killing 12 
Israelis in retaliation for the Hebron massacre of 30 Moslem 
worshippers by a Jewish settler. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

