<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sudanese Official, Habibi Discuss Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sudanese Official, Habibi Discuss Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004200894 Tehran IRNA in English 1753 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, April 20, IRNA -- Deputy Foreign Minister of 
Sudan Yusuf Baradah in his meeting with the First Deputy 
President of Iran Hasan Habibi said today that most of the 
problems faced by the Muslim countries have been imposed by the 
enemies of Islam. 
  "The enemies of Islam fear the awakening of Muslims in 
countries like Iran, Sudan, Algeria and Bosnia, and are 
therefore trying to suppress them by all possible means," 
Baradah pointed out. 
  He lauded the accomplishments of Islamic Iran and said the 
country is indebted to the unity of its people, its leadership 
and dedicated efforts of responsible officials. 
  Baradah who arrived in Tehran on Monday, said the purpose of 
his visit to Iran is become more familiar with the official 
views and positions for further developing of Tehran-Khartoum 
relations. 
  Habibi said in response that one of the ways for fighting 
problems in the Muslim world after steadfastness, and struggle 
and proper programming, is development of relations and exchange 
of views between the officials of Muslim countries. 
  He said the setting up of the Iran-Sudan joint economic 
commission has facilitated bilateral trade relations and 
suggested that the two sides should explore the grounds for 
private investments in the other country. 

</TEXT>

