<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Warns of Intensifying Nuclear Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Warns of Intensifying Nuclear Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2004144594 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2004144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan says India's assertion not to give up 
nuclear option under any circumstances would intensify the 
nuclear threat in South Asia and neighboring regions. This was 
stated by a Foreign Office spokesman in Islamabad today while 
commenting on a statement made by the Indian prime minister, Mr. 
Narasimha Rao, during his address to the Indian military 
commanders on the 13th of this month. He said Mr. Narasimha 
Rao's statement is clear manifestation of India's intention to 
persist with its nuclear-weapon program. The spokesman said 
when viewed in conjunction with India's reported intention to 
deploy ballistic missiles, the statement arouses the legitimate 
fear that India is about to take steps which will unleash a 
nuclear arms race in South Asia. He said it is no secret that 
India wants to be recognized as nuclear-weapon state to realize 
its image of itself as a great power. The Indian ambition, the 
spokesman said, will inevitably erode the nonproliferation 
regime of the NPT [Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty] which 
recognizes only five nuclear-weapon states. He said all that 
India needs to do to reassure itself about Pakistan's nuclear 
program is to accept one of the several proposals made by 
Pakistan for reciprocal or regional nonproliferation. The 
spokesman said India's stance can only be interpreted as a 
preemptory rejection of the proposal advanced recently by the 
United States about initiating multilateral talks on security in 
South Asia. 
  Commenting on the press reports about resumption of 
bilateral 
talks between India and Pakistan, the spokesman clarified that 
Pakistan has not received any proposal for ministerial or 
summit-level talks between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

