<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Previews Talks With 'Arafat in Bucharest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres Previews Talks With 'Arafat in Bucharest </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2004185594 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2004185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres left for 
Bucharest this evening and will meet there tonight with PLO 
leader, Yasir 'Arafat. In their talk the two will try to 
resolve the remaining disagreements. Minister Peres will also 
demand that 'Arafat supply information on the Israeli MIA's and 
captives. Our correspondent Dov Gilhar reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Gilhar] Bucharest is becoming another 
stop of the peace train. Peres has left for an international 
economic conference in Romania, where he will meet with 'Arafat 
in an attempt to overcome the last obstacles in the Cairo talks. 
  [Peres] Besides the MIA's issue, most of the talk will focus 
on how to bring about the conclusion of the negotiations from 
the viewpoint of issues, timetable, and arrangements. 
  [Gilhar] In the wake of the report you heard from Major 
General Shahaq this morning, do you believe it will be possible 
to conclude the negotiations by next weekend? 
  [Peres] I do not know if this will be the case indeed, but 
the impression is that we are at the final stage, and barring 
unexpected developments, we may be able to conclude the 
negotiations within two to three weeks. 
  [Gilhar] In tonight's meeting Peres will also demand to 
receive information on the MIA's issue. Before his departure 
Peres heard a report on significant progress on civilian matters 
at the Cairo talks. The Israeli delegation leaders came from 
Cairo to Jerusalem this morning to brief the foreign minister 
and prime minister on the remaining disputes. Rabin heard from 
Maj. Gen. Shahaq that the talks are delayed over the PLO's 
demands that Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] prisoners be 
released and that it exercise legal powers also regarding 
Israelis who move through the autonomy areas. [passage omitted] 
[end recording] 
  [Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network in Hebrew at 
1700 GMT on 20 April reports on the Cairo talks, adding that 
"several issues have remained unresolved in the deliberations of 
the Security Committee. The problem of the prisoners' release 
has not been solved yet, although an agreed timetable was 
already set for the release of 5,000 prisoners: 2,500 will be 
released upon the signing of the agreement, and the rest will be 
released three weeks after the signing. The Palestinians demand 
that a timetable be set for the release of another 3,500 
prisoners approximately, including Hamas members, but Israel is 
opposed to this." On civilian matters, "three questions remain 
open, and they will be transferred to 'Arafat and Rabin for 
decision: the question of area code for Gaza and Jericho; the 
Palestinian stamp; and the passport."] 

</TEXT>

