<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Arab Delegation Leaves for Jordan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Arab Delegation Leaves for Jordan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1704135994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1005 GMT 17 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1704135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A delegation of Muslim heads of local councils and 
clergymen left for Jordan today. Officially, the purpose of 
their visit is to attend the ceremony marking the end of the 
renovation of the al-Aqsa Mosque in Jerusalem, but knowledgeable 
sources say this is yet another attempt to court Israel's Arabs. 
Our correspondent Yo'el Dar has more details: 
  For many years, all Arab countries ignored their brethren 
living in Israel, especially the Muslims. Israel's Arabs were 
barred from visiting the Arab countries, making the pilgrimage 
to Mecca, and studying at Cairo's al-Azhar University. The Arab 
League, too, refused to recognize Israel's Arabs and treated 
them as agents and collaborators of the Zionists and the State 
of Israel. 
  Recently, however, earnest efforts have been made to court 
representatives of the Israeli Arab community. The PLO-Tunis 
embraced its secular circles, particularly HADASH [Democratic 
Front for Peace and Equality]; Egypt found its way to the heart 
of heads of local councils and activists in Darawshah's party; 
while Jordan and Saudi Arabia took clergymen and conservative 
circles under their wings. 
  A large group of heads of local councils and qadis left for 
Jordan today. The official purpose of their visit is to attend 
the celebrations marking the end of the renovation of al-Aqsa 
Mosque in Jerusalem. However, a look at the composition of the 
delegation shows that its members were not chosen at random and 
that the fact that it headed by a representative of the Islamic 
Movement is no mere coincidence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

