<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Game' of Israeli Working Papers Called `New Pretext' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Game' of Israeli Working Papers Called `New Pretext' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1804073194 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0450 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1804073194 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] TISHRIN comments on the peace process and Israel's 
unserious approach toward this process. The paper emphasizes 
that Syria is serious about the peace process and adds: Syria 
presented a document of principles during the sixth round of the 
Washington talks, which was hailed by the international 
community as a balanced, objective paper that lays the 
foundations of firm peace in the region. 
  The paper speaks about Israel's refusal to discuss the sixth 
item of the paper of principles on the exchange of land for 
peace and the return of the Golan. Israel inundated the 
Washington talks with an endless series of security conditions 
and pretexts, as if the Washington talks were held to provide 
security for Israel alone. 
  TISHRIN notes the settlement paper reported by Israel radio, 
stressing that the paper does not refer to Israel's willingness 
to withdraw fully from the Golan. The Israeli paper revolves 
around the achievement of great gains, such as relations, 
normalization and security arrangements. This confirms that 
there is no change in the Israeli position and that the approach 
of procrastination and maneuvering is still the same. 
  TISHRIN adds: Obviously, the game of the Israeli working 
papers -- one for the Army and another for the Foreign Ministry 
-- is only a new pretext to escape the obligations of the peace 
process, primarily withdrawal from the Golan and the rest of the 
occupied territories. 
  The Washington talks have extensively addressed all items 
related to peace, particularly security arrangements. However, 
the Israeli side has repeatedly refused to discuss the question 
of withdrawal. Had Israel truly wanted peace, the question would 
not have taken all these discussions, deliberations, and working 
papers. Security Council resolutions, the Madrid conference 
foundations, and the U.S. initiative all stem from the exchange 
of land for peace. 
  TISHRIN concludes by reasserting that Syria is not willing 
to 
relinquish an inch of its territory or any Arab right. Syria is 
also not willing to exchange facts for illusions and to replace 
the Washington talks and the Madrid conference foundations by 
secret talks whose only aim is to circumvent the Security 
Council resolutions. 
  Under the headline "Rejected Call," AL-BA'TH says: News 
reports speak once again about an upcoming tour to the region by 
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher late this month. 
Israel is also talking about what it called two papers on a 
settlement with Syria. The head of its government, Rabin, 
stressed the need for secret talks that would pave the way for 
the settlement. 
  AL-BA'TH adds: We can draw several conclusions in this 
regard, primarily the return of the U.S. Administration to the 
Middle East arena in a fresh bid to advance peace efforts by 
fixing a date for resuming bilateral talks. 
  Before moving on to the Israeli position, we must wonder how 
far Christopher will go in his upcoming tour. Will he view 
Rabin's statements as something new? 
  AL-BA'TH concludes: It is too early to pass judgment in this 
regard, since this depends on the way the U.S. secretary will 
deal with the Israeli government. 

</TEXT>

