<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iraqi Diplomats Deported; Officials Comment on Dispute </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iraqi Diplomats Deported; Officials Comment on Dispute </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Buwayz Comments on Diplomats </H4>

<F P=102> NC2004170494 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1530 GMT 20 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2004170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [News conference by Foreign Minister Faris Buwayz with </F>
unidentified correspondents in Beirut on 20 April--recorded] 
  [Text] [Buwayz] Today we are dealing with some issues 
relating to decisions that have already been made. The 
deportation of the Iraqi diplomats might not be carried out 
tomorrow [words indistinct]. 
  [Correspondent] [Question indistinct]? 
  [Buwayz] There is a problem and [words indistinct] by 
tomorrow. 
  [Correspondent] [Words indistinct] will U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher tour the Middle East? 
  [Buwayz] Yes. 
  [Correspondent] When? 
  [Buwayz] No dates have been given. I believe it will be next 
week. 
  [Correspondent] Do you know whether he will come to Lebanon? 
  [Buwayz] No. I don't know. 
  [Correspondent] [Question indistinct]? 
  [Buwayz] The issue is a legal one. [Words indistinct] it was 
a political decision that the government had to make. It did 
so. It decided to sever relations and to deport the diplomats 
who are here. As for the judiciary decision, since there is 
immunity in this particular case and in view of the overall 
circumstances of the case, it is up to the court to decide. The 
court, the judiciary, will be the one that will take the Vienna 
Convention and its own interpretations and apply them to this 
case. It will decide either that this case falls within the 
context of the Vienna Convention and, therefore, there is 
immunity or that the circumstances are beyond the Vienna 
Convention and that the Lebanese judiciary is not qualified to 
decide on the issue. The decision is up to the judiciary. 
  [Correspondent] Which judiciary? 
  [Buwayz] By judiciary I mean the court. 
  [Correspondent] Minister, Iraq is asking for the Lebanese 
investigation committee, is it not.... 
  [Buwayz, interrupting] The state's employees should stop 
speculating. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

